Upon review of the CDR, some disparities in the informant's responses emerged that support our decision to score the memory box as 0 and check 'yes' to inclusion criteria question no.2. Although the informant states that the memory problem is consistent, she says he can usually recall events and remember a list of items. She says his memory does not interfere with his daily functioning, he rarely forgets major events, details, and info regarding the distant past. Second, the subject may perceive to have a consistent memory problem, but he correctly answered all questions on page 7, except for some things about memory within the past month. Both the subject's performance along with the informant's responses seem to offset their perceptions that he indeed has a consistent memory problem. Thus, we strongly feel that the subject does not have a consistent memory problem, so the inclusion criteria no.2 can be answered yes. This was reviewed by the clinical monitor and Mario Schittini.

I just wanted to note that this subject's screening MRI took place on Sat 12/16/2006. Before entering scanner, subject mentioned that he used to have a pacemaker but had it removed. Neither he nor study partner had ever mentioned this in questions about medical history, previous surgery, MRI safety screening forms, etc.  MRI tech noted that sometimes surgeons leave pacing wires inside the chest when they remove the pacemaker. Study partner was unsure whether the wires were left in chest or not. MRI tech took participant to have a chest X-ray - no wires noted in X-ray, and subject completed scan safely and successfully. This X-ray will now be on file at our site for future scans. I will add this pacemaker removal to his medical history.  I assume I don't need to note the chest X-ray as an AE, because it is covered in our consent form - it notes that sometimes an X-ray may be necessary to ascertain MRI safety.  Please alert me if more needs to be done regarding this issue.

The subject had a lumbar puncture for the study on 12/01/2006. He apparently developed back pain in 02/07, with a flu-like illness, which resolved after one week. The back pain persisted, and worsened, and he developed fatigue with weight loss, with intermittent response to treatment. In 07/07, he had a CT scan of the spine, which demonstrated abnormal signal within the L4 and L5 vertebral bodies and edema in the adjacent disk. Most of the pathology was in the anterior portion of the lumbar spine, rather than the posterior portion. The patient had a biopsy in hospital on 7/19/07, and the culture was positive for Actinomyces. He was started on IV Ceftriaxone, and his symptoms subsequently improved and a repeat CT scan on 9/26 showed good resolution of the inflammatory changes.

The Boston Naming Test had administration errors involving the semantic cues but the errors did not affect the final score. (Kelly Blackmer, 8/6/2012)

Three administration errors occurred on the BNT: 1.) Item 41 - the semantic cue was given in error because the initial response 'sea gull' is not a misperception of the pelican image. 2.) Item 55 - the semantic cue was given in error because the initial responses 'spinx' and 'finx' are not misperceptions of the sphynx image. 3.) Item 57 - the semantic cue was given in error because the initial response 'arbor' is not a misperception of the trellis image. Since the semantic cue should not have been given, this item cannot be added to the Total Correct score. Note: this causes a discrepancy between source document and EDC record, where the Semantic Cue Correct score had to be entered as '0.'

On 11/30/2012, principal investigator provided an explanation for making an exception for participant 5039, despite having an MMSE score of 17, which is typically exclusionary. P.I. stated, 'I believe EJM (Subject number 010-S-5039) should be enrolled in ADNI.  The patient has a progressive change in memory and cognitive function that includes word-finding difficulty without focal neurologic or parkinsonian findings or significant personality or behavioral manifestations.  Melanie Shulman, MD a board certified behavioral neurologist has provided a diagnosis of mild Alzheimer[|226|][|128|][|153|]s disease with logopenia. After a review of the records, I concur with this diagnosis.  I believe that the MMSE score of 17 is spurious due to difficulty finding the correct words for the day, date, year and place of examination rather than an issue with orientation.  I would request an exemption to enroll this very interested individual into ADNI.' - Dr. James Galvin.

Additional notes from clinician regarding adverse event 6 - hosptialization for delirium and elevated troponin: According to notes from 1/15/13, she presented to her primary MD w/ complaints of fatigue/malaise and increased somnolence over 2 weeks. She was afebrile and had normal vital signs at that visit. Her exam was unremarkable. Her chest x-ray on 1/15/13 did not show any acute process. She had a TSH, CBC, and metabolic panel were ordered, but I do not see any results in her medical record from that day. She was admitted overnight on 1/21-1/22/13 with complaints of continued fatigue and new onset confusion, headache, and feeling clammy/sweaty. Her confusion resolved before she was seen by the attending physician. She was afebrile. Her white blood cell count was elevated at 16.9 at admission (normal differential). She had a normal chest x-ray, urinalysis, and was negative for influenza. They did not do an LP. Her cardiac enzymes were elevated (troponins were 2.63 on admission and trended downward overnight).  ECGs showed lateral t-wave abnormalities, but no ST-T wave changes. WBC ct was normal the next day at 9.0. There was some concern about whether her CPAP settings were optimal and she was seen by pulmonary team as an inpatient and they recommended repeat sleep study.

The subject did not fall within the required cognitive testing parameters for acceptance onto the ADNI study.  Both the subject and informant were informed of this. The subject was disappointed, however, he was advised that he would be welcome to rescreen for ADNI in a couple of months.  They left Johns Hopkins to return to their home.Later that afternoon, Dan D[|226|][|128|][|153|]Agostino, ADNI Study Coordinator, received a call from the subject, who seemed to be highly emotional. His long history of depression, and a documented suicide attempt following the death of his mother in about 2002, led the team to feel very concerned about potential outcomes of the subject[|226|][|128|][|153|]s current emotional state. The matter was discussed with the study primary investigator, Dr. Marilyn Albert, and it was agreed that we should call the caregiver to make her aware of the situation.The caregiver was very happy to receive our call, and very appreciative of our concern. She told us that the subject shared with her, after the fact, that he had made a call to Dan, at Johns Hopkins. She told Leonie that she had spent some time with him helping him to process the outcome of today[|226|][|128|][|153|]s visit, and that he now seemed to be feeling better. Leonie invited the caregiver to make contact with the study at any time if she has any questions or concerns. It was decided amongst the study team later that afternoon that the subject is too emotionally unstable to participate in ADNI-2, therefore, he will not be brought back in for a rescreen.

After review of the participant[|226|][|128|][|153|]s discharge summary for this event, the following information is available:  The participant presented to her PCP complaining of chest pain in a crescendo pattern over a few days leading up to the incident.  She was sent to her primary cardiologist, who noted new anterior T-wave changes across her precordium on her EKG and sent her to Rhode Island Hospital for cardiac catheterization to take place on the morning of 10/22/2013.  The participant was admitted to Rhode Island Hospital on 10/21/2013, but was chest pain-free upon arrival.  The pt was admitted to the ICCU on her usual medical therapy.  She was Plavix loaded with 600 mg of Plavix, continued on full strength aspirin and made n.p.o. for catheterization in the AM.  During the night prior to the catheterization, the pt woke up at 5:00 AM complaining of chest pain.  Her blood pressure was noted to be elevated at that time at 220/70 with a heart rate in the 60s.  She was given sublingual nitroglycerin, which helped her chest pain.  Her EKG at that time showed ST elevations in V1 through V3 with ST depressions in V4 through (cont.)

V6.  She was started on nitroglycerin drip for elevated blood pressure of the 180s after the nitroglycerin.  The drip was titrated up to control her blood pressure.  She remained pain-free after the event.  Troponin was checked and it was negative.  Because of the pt[|226|][|128|][|153|]s ST elevations and chest pain, the Catheterization Lab was notified.  The pt was taken to the catheterization lab as first case.  She underwent a cardiac catheterization with Dr. George McKendall.  Catheterization showed the following; on October 22, 2013: Left ventricular and diastolic pressure was normal, LV showed mild focal apical hypokinesis.  Ejection fraction was normal.  The left main was normal.  The LAD had a mid 85% stenosis that when compared to her last catheterization had progressed.  The lesion occurred at the argon of a small diffusely diseased diagonal branch, which also had an 85% lesion.  The left circumflex showed a widely patent stent.  The right artery RCA showed a previously deployed patent stent with some distal irregularities.  The patient underwent an LAD PCI with a 3.25x18 drug-eluting stent with good distal flow and returned to the ICCU in improved condition.  (cont.)

The pt. had no recurrent pain.  Her blood pressure was improved post-procedure.  She had the procedure done via her right radial artery.  A TR band was in place and there were no problems with hematoma.  The pt. was re-seen later that day with a blood pressure at that time, 4:00 PM of 116/53, pulse of 68.  TR band was removed.  There was no hematoma or bleeding.  There was a strong pulse.  On the day of discharge home on October 23, 2013, the pt. remained asymptomatic with no recurrent chest pain.  She had been out of bed and ambulating.  She had no recurrent symptoms.  Additionally, her blood pressure remained in control.  Her blood pressure on exam was 128/52, heart rate of 72.  She was saturating 98% on room air.  She felt much better.  Her labs were significant for normal troponin x2.  Creatinine was also normal at 0.77.  Potassium was low at 3.0.  That was repeated with 60 mEq of p.o. potassium at breakfast and another 40 mEq later at lunch.  The patient was otherwise ready for discharge home.  Her EKG showed sinus rhythm, heart rate of 67, borderline IVCD with poor R-wave (cont.)
progression, T-wave inversions in V2 through V6, but improved when compared to October 22, 2013.

In early July 2011 he was not feeling well while driving from Rhode                     Island with his wife as a passenger in the car and accordingly stayed in                     the right hand lane.  He then became confused and ran up onto the curb.  He                     was still conversational at that time.  She put him in the passenger seat                     and belted him.  Then she drove on, and his condition worsened.  He became                     quiet, then displayed rocking movements in the car, hanging onto the                     handle.  He became diaphoretic and started picking at his pants and then                     gave forth unintelligible words and nonsense.  He appeared to be aphasic.                     He was alert the whole time, extraocular movements were intact and there                     were no adventitial or tonic-clonic movements.  By the time they arrived at                     their destination on the Cape, he was becoming unmanageably agitated, as                     the ambulance arrived from Mashpee, he was frankly combative. He required                     sedation, intubation and transfer to the ICU. He was given antihypertensives and sedation. Blood pressure                     dropped precipitously with bradycardia and he was started on dopamine and                     dobutamine.  By the next morning, he was moving all extremities but still                     agitated.  The presentation gradually improved, and he was discharged after                     a 5-day admission.

A lumbar puncture was done in seated position. Local anesthesia was administered (2% Lidocaine). A 24G sprottle needle was inserted in the L3-L4 space. During the procedure, and before obtaining CSF, the patient complained of cramps and dizziness. After a few minutes, the patient could not hold the position anymore and fainted for a few seconds. After the incident, the subject did not complain of back pain, chest pain, shortness of breath or headache. The procedure was interrupted, and the patient was placed lying down on her back. After a few minutes, the subject recovered entirely and the dizziness stopped. After 15 minutes, the subject was able to stand up again without any issues. The vital signs were normal before and after the procedure. The patient did not report any complaint after the procedure.

CASPECIF: Psychometric battery - MMSE and Logical Memory
CACOMM:
At the end of the clinical assessment visit (8/21/2017), we discovered that this participant had been exposed to components of the psychometric battery during participation in an affiliated center-wide project on 5/25/2017.  We have since followed up with our affiliated project to ensure that they check with our main clinical research office before enrolling a new participant.  At the 5/25/2017 visit, the participant completed a battery that included the MMSE and the Logical Memory tests.

- The 5/25/2017 Logical Memory version used the Anna Thompson story. We will plan to use the Greg Fortune version of the ADNI3 psychometric session scheduled for 8/31/2017.

This subject presented to ADRC for ADNI-3 baseline procedures of blood work and lumbar puncture.  Last  meal was 8:00pm on June 6, 2018.and per protocol has been fasting since then.  She continued to hydrate with water throughout that time.  She had blood work drawn approximately at 8:50am following which she complained of nausea then had a syncopal episode fo approximately 30 seconds.  Subject was placed supine on exam table.  She continued to hydrate with water. Blood pressure was 112/66 P 76 supine, standing 94/60 P 88.  She complained of recurrent nausea with standing that mostly resolved with supine position. As per baseline protocol subject had EKG done which showed HR 61 and no ectopy.  Dr. Neelesh Nadkarni evaluated subject; he was to do LP. No c/o hotheadedness, headache,diplopia.  Subject did c/o diaphoresis. Subject had vomiting when she attempted to stand for a length of time.  After emesis nausea improved and she ambulated independently to waiting room.  It was the recommendation of Dr. Nadkarni that she receive evaluation at ER for orthostasis however was agreeable for subject to stay in waiting room and re assess.  Upon reassessment at 10:20  am supine BP 120/68 P 68, sitting 110/70 P 72, standing 100/70 P 80. First attempt at standing failed as subject c/o nausea upon standing after supine.  With second attempt of standing subject continued to c/o nausea.  Subject and husband discussed preferene to be seen by PCP. Discussed with Dr. Nadkarni.  Husband made appointment for this afternoon at 2pm.  Advised that subject call 911 if symptoms worsen or if immediate medical attention needed.  Subject and husband voiced understanding.  Subject was stable and ambulatory and left waiting room area.  Obtained ROI and spoke with PCP, Dr. McIntyre (724-593-5919) to discuss events.
